ative province. These are the stories of women whose voices may otherwise never have been heard: entry-level workers at fledgling shelters battling the assumption that their facilities would create crime, small-town shelter directors forced to self-censor or lose communityand financialsupport, Indigenous women fighting to serve their sisters in Indigenous spaces. Beginning with the women who founded the first shelters, and continuing through the establishment of the Alberta Council of Women's Shelters to the present day, We Need to Do This is a story of hope and survival for the women’s shelter movement and for the mothers, sisters, aunts, cousins, and daughters it continues to serve.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Abuse / Domestic Partner Abuse.2bisacsh  aalberta.  acanada.  acommunity activism.  adomestic disputes.  adomestic violence.  afeminism.  agender based violence.  ahistory.  aintimate partner violence.  aviolence intervention.  aviolence prevention.  aviolence response.  awomen.  awomen’s safety.  awomen’s shelters.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781773854946?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781773854946423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781773854946/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles